  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is due to an assertion
failure in BoUpSLP::getLastInstructionInBundle. The assertion expects that all
scalars in a bundle reside in the same basic block unless they are (a) gathered
loads earmarked for special treatment or (b) vector-like instructions with
constant operands or (c) for GEP entries, non-GEP Values (like constants/args).
In the provided reproducer, SLP vectorizes GEP indices across multiple basic
blocks (bb and bb3) and forms a gather node for sign/zero-extends. These are
legal to gather but they violate the assertion, which only whitelists gathered
loads when across blocks.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows
vectorizeGEPIndices collected 4 indices and decided to vectorize the list at cost
5. The gather node comprises zext/sext instructions %zext, %zext2, %sext (in bb)
and %zext6 (in bb3). The first transformation point is
getLastInstructionInBundle, which computes and sets the insertion point. The
assertion checks that cross-BB bundles are either gathered loads or
\"vector-like\" ops with const operands. Here, the opcode of the entry is 39 (an
extend/GEP-index node), isGather() is true, and some scalars come from different
BBs. Since it's not a load, the assertion fails.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nvectorizeGEPIndices builds a gather node of index-producing
instructions (zext/sext/constants), which is valid. The helper
getLastInstructionInBundle has an overly restrictive assertion that only
tolerates gathered loads across blocks, not arbitrary gathered nodes. Subsequent
logic (FindLastInst/FindFirstInst) already handles cross-block insertion points
using dominance and reachability, but the assertion prevents proceeding. There
are similar assertions inside FindLastInst and FindFirstInst that also whitelist
only gathered loads for cross-BB cases.\n\nTherefore, the root cause is the
assertion policy being too narrow: it assumes only gathered loads may span
multiple blocks, while SLP now also builds gathered entries for GEP indices and
potentially other patterns.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should relax the
assertions to allow any gathered entries to span multiple basic blocks, not just
gathered loads. The scheduling/insertion code already accounts for cross-block
bundles using dominance checks.\n\n- Edit 1 (lines 13048-13061): Broaden the
condition to allow E->isGather() across BBs, not only gathered loads. Replace the
current condition\n  ((GatheredLoadsEntriesFirst.has_value() && E->getOpcode() ==
Instruction::Load && E->isGather() && E->Idx < *GatheredLoadsEntriesFirst) ||
all_of(...))\n  with\n  (E->isGather() || all_of(...))\n  This preserves the
existing checks for non-gather bundles while allowing any gather bundle to have
instructions in different BBs.\n\n- Edit 2 (lines 13074-13082): In FindLastInst,
relax the assert for cross-BB scalars. Currently, it only allows the cross-BB
case for gathered loads. Add E->isGather() to the allowed cases so it becomes:\n
assert(((E->getOpcode() == Instruction::GetElementPtr &&
!isa<GetElementPtrInst>(I)) || (isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(LastInst) &&
isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(I)) || E->isGather()) && ...);\n\n- Edit 3 (lines
13113-13118): In FindFirstInst, similarly relax the assert to allow general
gathered entries across BBs by adding E->isGather() to the disjunction:\n
assert(((E->getOpcode() == Instruction::GetElementPtr &&
!isa<GetElementPtrInst>(I)) || (isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(FirstInst) &&
isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(I)) || E->isGather()) && ...);\n\nThese changes
acknowledge that SLP may construct gather nodes from different BBs (e.g., index
computations), and rely on dominance/reachability logic to place the insertion
point correctly.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by an overly strict
assertion that only permits gathered loads to span multiple basic blocks.
vectorizeGEPIndices legitimately constructs a gather of index-producing extends
that reside in different BBs. Relaxing the assertions in
getLastInstructionInBundle, FindLastInst, and FindFirstInst to allow any gathered
entries across BBs resolves the crash and lets the pass compute insertion points
using the existing dominance-aware logic. This fix does not alter transformation
semantics but prevents erroneous aborts on valid IR patterns.",
